{"title_page": "Anastasian War", "text_new": "{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Anastasian War\n| partof      = the [[Roman-Persian Wars]]\n| image       = [[File:Roman-Persian Frontier in Late Antiquity.svg|250px|The Roman-Persian frontier had remained stable since 384, when the two powers divided Armenia, and despite recurrent warfare, would not change significantly until the Lazic War]]\n| image_size  =\n| alt         =\n| caption     = The Roman-Persian frontier had remained stable since 384, when the two powers divided Armenia, and despite recurrent warfare, would not change significantly until the [[Lazic War]].\n| date        = 502\u2013506 AD\n| place       = [[Osroene]], [[Upper Mesopotamia]], [[Armenia]], [[Southeastern Anatolia Region, Turkey|Southeastern Anatolia]]\n| coordinates = \n| map_type    = \n| map_relief  = \n| map_size    = \n| map_marksize = \n| map_caption = \n| map_label   = \n| territory   = The Sassanian Empire captures [[Erzurum|Theodosiopolis]] and [[Silvan, Diyarbak\u0131r|Martyropolis]]\n| result      = Peace treaty<br>The [[Byzantine Empire]] pays 1,000 pounds of gold to the [[Sassanid Empire]]<ref name=\"IO\">http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/sasanian-dynasty</ref>\n| combatant1  = [[Byzantine Empire]]<br>Arab allies\n| combatant2  = [[Sasanian Empire]]<br>[[Lakhmids]]\n| commander1  = {{plainlist|\n*[[Anastasius I (emperor)|Anastasius I]]\n*[[Areobindus Dagalaiphus Areobindus|Areobindus]]\n*[[Patricius (consul 500)|Patricius]]\n*[[Hypatius (consul 500)|Hypatius]]\n*[[Apion (family)|Apion]]\n*[[Justin I]]\n*[[Patriciolus]]\n*[[Vitalian (general)|Vitalian]]\n*[[Pharesmanes]]\n*[[Celer (magister officiorum)|Celer]]\n*[[Romanus (dux)|Romanus]]\n*[[Constantine (comes rei militaris)|Constantine]]{{POW}}<ref>The sources are contradictory about the role played by Constantine during the siege of Theodosiopolis. According to [[Zacharias Rhetor]], ({{harvnb|Greatrex|2002|p=63}}) he was taken prisoner, while according to [[Joshua the Stylite]], due a grudge he bore against the emperor Anastasius, he betrayed the Romans.({{harvnb|Martindale|1980|p=314}})</ref>\n*Godidisklus\n*[[Bessas (general)|Bessas]]\n*[[Rufinus (patricius)|Rufinus]]\n*Asouades\n*Bonosus\n*Timostratus\n}}\n| commander2  = {{plainlist|\n*[[Kavadh I]]\n*Theodore\n*[[Al-Mundhir III ibn al-Nu'man]]\n*[[Adergoudounbades]]\n*[[Bawi]]\n*[[Glones]]{{KIA}}\n*Mirranes ([[Perozes]]?)\n}}\n| units1      = \n| units2      = \n| strength1   = \n| strength2   = \n| casualties1 = \n| casualties2 = \n| notes       = \n| campaignbox = {{Campaignbox Roman-Persian Wars}}\n{{Campaignbox Anastasian War}}\n}}\nThe '''Anastasian War''' was fought from 502 to 506 between the [[Byzantine Empire]] and the [[Sasanian Empire]]. It was the first major conflict between the two powers since 440, and would be the prelude to a long [[Byzantine-Sassanid Wars|series of destructive conflicts]] between the two empires over the next century.\n\n==Prelude==\nSeveral factors underlay the termination of the longest period of peace the [[Byzantine Empire|Eastern Roman]] and the [[Sassanid Empire]] ever enjoyed. The Persian king [[Kavadh I]] needed money to pay his debts to the [[Hephthalites]] who had helped him regain his throne in 498/499. The situation was exacerbated by recent changes in the flow of the [[Tigris]] in [[Lower Mesopotamia]], sparking famines and flood. When the Roman emperor [[Anastasius I (emperor)|Anastasius I]] refused to provide any help, Kavadh tried to gain the money by force.<ref>Procopius. ''History of the Wars'', I.7.1-2; {{harvnb|Greatrex|Lieu|2002|p=62}}.</ref>\n\n==War==\n\n[[File:NE 500ad.jpg|thumb|left|175px|Roman and Persian Empires in 500, also showing their neighbors, many of whom were dragged into wars between the great powers.]]\n\n===Kavadh I's campaign of 502===\n\nIn 502, Kavadh quickly captured the unprepared city of [[Theodosiopolis (Armenia)|Theodosiopolis]], perhaps with local support; the city was in any case undefended by troops and weakly fortified.<ref>{{harvnb|Greatrex|Lieu|2002|p=62}}.</ref> [[Martyropolis]] also [[Siege of Martyropolis (502)|fell]] in the same year. Kavadh then besieged the fortress-city of [[Amida (Roman city)|Amida]] through the autumn and winter (502-503) and captured it after a lengthy siege, although the defenders were unsupported by troops.<ref>{{harvnb|Greatrex|Lieu|2002|p=63}}.</ref> Many people, particularly the population of Amida, were [[deportation|deported]] to [[Pars (Sasanian province)|Pars]] and [[Khuzestan]] in Persia, in particular, to the new city of [[Veh-az-Amid Kavad]] (Arrajan).<ref>A. Shapur Shahbazi, Erich Kettenhofen, John R. Perry, \u201cDEPORTATIONS,\u201d ''[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Iranica]]'', VII/3, pp. 297-312, available online at http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/deportations (accessed on 30 December 2012).</ref>\n\n===Anastasius' campaign of 503 and Kavad I's counterattack===\n\nThe Byzantine emperor [[Anastasius I (emperor)|Anastasius I]] dispatched an army in May 503 against the Sasanians. The army was the largest Roman force in the East since [[Julian's Persian War|Julian's invasion of Persia]]. The force gathered at [[Edessa]] and [[Samosata]]. It operated in three divisions under ''[[magister militum per Orientem]]'' [[Areobindus Dagalaiphus Areobindus|Areobindus]], ''[[strategos]]'' [[Patricius (consul 500)|Patricius]], and [[Hypatius (consul 500)|Hypatius]]. Hypatius and Patricius attacked Amida, which was held by a 3,000-strong garrison under [[Glones]]. Areobindus, together with [[Romanus (dux)|Romanus]] and thee Arab ''[[phylarch]]'' Asouades (Aswad) (probably a [[Kindah]] leader) attacked [[Nisibis]], in which Kavadh I was residing.<ref name=\"Heather\">{{cite book |last1=Heather |first1=Peter J. |title=Rome Resurgent: War and Empire in the Age of Justinian |date=2018 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-936274-5 |page=77 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Shahid |first1=Irfan |title=Byzantium and the Arabs in the Sixth Century |date=1995 |publisher=Dumbarton Oaks |isbn=978-0-88402-214-5 |page=21 |language=en}}</ref> Procopius also mentions Patricias the Phrygian as a fourth commander.<ref name=\"Procopius62\" /> Notable officers associated with this force include ''\"[[hyparch]]\"'' [[Apion (family)|Apion I]] (the Egyptian),<ref>{{cite book |last1=Bury |first1=John Bagnell |title=History of the Later Roman Empire from the Death of Theodosius I. to the Death of Justinian |date=1958 |publisher=Courier Corporation |isbn=978-0-486-20398-0 |page=471 |language=en}}</ref> ''[[comes]]'' [[Justin I|Justin]] (the future emperor),<ref name=\"Dodgeon\" />  [[Patriciolus]] and his son [[Vitalian (general)|Vitalian]] (who later revolted against Anastasius), the Colchian [[Pharesmanes]], and the Goths Godidisklus and [[Bessas (general)|Bessas]].<ref name=\"Procopius62\">{{cite book |author1=Procopius of Caesarea |authorlink1=Procopius of Caesarea |title=History of the Wars: Books 1-2 (Persian War) |date=2007 |publisher=Cosimo, Inc. |isbn=978-1-60206-445-4 |pages=62-63 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=toHxDMLTJ4MC&lpg=PA63&pg=PA63 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nInitially, Areobindus gained the upper hand in Nisibis, but Kavadh I's counterattack defeated him, plundered his fort Apadna, and forced him to retreat westward; Hypatius and Patricius attempted to assist him, but it was too late.<ref name=\"Heather\" /> They failed to join with Areobindus and were decisively defeated between Apadna and [[Tell Beshme]] and retreated to Samosata. According to Zacharias, their cavalry suffered heavily during the retreat, falling from the cliffs of mountains. Kavadh continued westward to [[Constantia (Osrhoene)|Constantia]] but failed to capture it, though received supplies from its inhabitants. In early September, Kacadh reached near Edessa. Areobindus rejected Kavadh I's demand of {{convert|10,000|lb}} of gold in exchange for peace. Sasanians and [[Lakhmids]]s overran much of Osrhoene but attempts to attack the fortified city failed. Meanwhile, Byzantine forces under [[Pharesmanes]] attacked Amida, who killed the Sasanian commander [[Glones]] through cunning. This, together with Hunnic incursions, the arrival of Byzantine reinforcements, and Kavadh I's lack of supplies, all forced him to withdraw to Persia. This further contributed to the reputation of Edessa as being impregnable.<ref name=\"Dodgeon\">{{cite book |last1=Dodgeon |first1=Michael H. |last2=Lieu |first2=Samuel N. C. |title=The Roman Eastern Frontier and the Persian Wars Ad 363-628 |date=1991 |publisher=Psychology Press |isbn=978-0-415-46530-4 |pages=68-72 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Greatrex|Lieu|2002|pp=69\u201371}}.</ref> Meanwhile, the ''dux'' of Osrhoene, Timostratus, defeated the Lakhmids, and the [[Tha'labites]] (Byzantine Arabs) attacked Lakhmid capital [[al-Hira]].<ref name=\"Dodgeon\" />\n\n===Anastasius' renewed assault===\n\nIn the summer of 503, Anastasius sent reinforcements under ''[[magister officiorum]]'' [[Celer (magister officiorum)|Celer]] and canceled taxes from Mesopotamia and Osrhoene, while Hypatius and Apion were recalled. Patricius moved to Amida, defeated a force sent against him, and invested the city; Celer joined him later in the spring of 504. While the siege was ongoing, Celer raided [[Beth Arabaye]], while Areobindus raided [[Arzanene]]. Sasanian weakness at this point is apparent by defections to the Byzantine side by the renegade Constantine, a certain Arab chief Adid, and the Armenian Mushlek. The Byzantines eventually captured Amida.<ref name=\"Greatrex-Lieu (2002), 77\" /><ref name=\"Dodgeon\" />\n\n===Peace treaty===\n\nIn the same year, an armistice was agreed as a result of an invasion of Armenia by the [[Hun]]s from the Caucasus. Negotiations between the two powers took place, but such was the distrust that in 506 the Romans, suspecting treachery, seized the Persian officials; once released, the Persians preferred to stay in [[Nisibis]].<ref name=\"Greatrex-Lieu (2002), 77\">{{harvnb|Greatrex|Lieu|2002|p=77}}.</ref> In November 506, a treaty was finally agreed, but little is known of what the terms of the treaty were. [[Procopius]] states that peace was agreed for seven years, and it is likely that some payments were made to the Persians.<ref>Procopius. ''History of the Wars'', I.9.24; {{harvnb|Greatrex|Lieu|2002|p=77}}.</ref> The Persians did not keep Byzantine territory and no annual tribute was paid so it seems the peace treaty was not harsh on the Byzantines.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Rome resurgent : war and empire in the age of Justinian|last=Heather, P. J. (Peter J.)|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2018|isbn=9780199362745|location=New York, NY|pages=|oclc=1007044617}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe Roman generals blamed many of their difficulties in this war on their lack of a major base in the immediate vicinity of the frontier, a role filled for the Persians by Nisibis (which until its secession in 363 had served the same purpose for the Romans), and in 505 Anastasius therefore ordered the building of a great fortified city at [[Dara (Mesopotamia)|Dara]]. The dilapidated fortifications were also upgraded at Edessa, [[Batnae]] and Amida.<ref>{{harvnb|Greatrex|Lieu|2002|p=74}}.</ref>\n\nAlthough no further large-scale conflict took place during Anastasius's reign, tensions continued, especially while work continued at Dara. This construction project was to become a key component of the Roman defenses, and also a lasting source of controversy with the Persians, who complained that its construction violated the treaty agreed in 422, by which both empires had agreed not to establish new fortifications in the frontier zone. Anastasius, however, pursued the project, deflecting Kavadh's complaints with money.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/belisariuslastro00ianh|title=Belisarius : the last Roman general|last=Hughes, Ian (Historian)|date=2009|publisher=Westholme|isbn=9781594160851|location=Yardley, Pa.|oclc=294885267|url-access=registration}}</ref> The Persians were in any case unable to stop the work, and the walls were completed by 507/508.<ref name=\"Greatrex-Lieu (2002), 77\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Sources==\n\n===Primary===\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Procopius|last2=Dewing|first2=H. B. (trans.)|title=History of the Wars|url=https://archive.org/details/b24750281_0001}} [http://www.gutenberg.org/files/16764/16764-8.txt Books I\u2013II].\n{{refend}}\n\n===Secondary===\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|last=Greatrex|first=Geoffrey|last2=Lieu|first2=Samuel N. C.|title=The Roman Eastern Frontier and the Persian Wars (Part II, 363\u2013630 AD)|location=New York, New York and London, United Kingdom|publisher=Routledge (Taylor & Francis)|year=2002|isbn=0-415-14687-9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zc8iAQAAIAAJ|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n[[Category:500s in the Byzantine Empire]]\n[[Category:6th century in Iran]]\n[[Category:500s conflicts]]\n[[Category:Roman\u2013Sasanian Wars]]\n[[Category:6th century in Asia]]\n[[Category:500s]]\n[[Category:502]]\n[[Category:506]]\n[[Category:Anastasian War| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Anastasian War\n| partof      = the [[Roman-Persian Wars]]\n| image       = [[File:Roman-Persian Frontier in Late Antiquity.svg|250px|The Roman-Persian frontier had remained stable since 384, when the two powers divided Armenia, and despite recurrent warfare, would not change significantly until the Lazic War]]\n| image_size  =\n| alt         =\n| caption     = The Roman-Persian frontier had remained stable since 384, when the two powers divided Armenia, and despite recurrent warfare, would not change significantly until the [[Lazic War]].\n| date        = 502\u2013506 AD\n| place       = [[Osroene]], [[Upper Mesopotamia]], [[Armenia]], [[Southeastern Anatolia Region, Turkey|Southeastern Anatolia]]\n| coordinates = \n| map_type    = \n| map_relief  = \n