g [[Byzantine-Sassanid Wars|series of destructive conflicts]] between the two empires over the next century.\n\n==Prelude==\nSeveral factors underlay the termination of the longest period of peace the [[Byzantine Empire|Eastern Roman]] and the [[Sassanid Empire]] ever enjoyed. The Persian king [[Kavadh I]] needed money to pay his debts to the [[Hephthalites]] who had helped him regain his throne in 498/499. The situation was exacerbated by recent changes in the flow of the [[Tigris]] in [[Lower Mesopotamia]], sparking famines and flood. When the Roman emperor [[Anastasius I (emperor)|Anastasius I]] refused to provide any help, Kavadh tried to gain the money by force.<ref>Procopius. ''History of the Wars'', I.7.1-2; {{harvnb|Greatrex|Lieu|2002|p=62}}.</ref>\n\n==War==\n\n[[File:NE 500ad.jpg|thumb|left|175px|Roman and Persian Empires in 500, also showing their neighbors, many of whom were dragged into wars between the great powers.]]\n\n===Kavadh I's campaign of 502===\n\nIn 502, Kavadh quickly captured the unprepared city of [[Theodosiopolis (Armenia)|Theodosiopolis]], perhaps with local support; the city was in any case undefended by troops and weakly fortified.<ref>{{harvnb|Greatrex|Lieu|2002|p=62}}.</ref> [[Martyropolis]] also [[Siege of Martyropolis (502)|fell]] in the same year. Kavadh then besieged the fortress-city of [[Amida (Roman city)|Amida]] through the autumn and winter (502-503) and captured it after a lengthy siege, although the defenders were unsupported by troops.<ref>{{harvnb|Greatrex|Lieu|2002|p=63}}.</ref> Many people, particularly the population of Amida, were [[deportation|deported]] to [[Pars (Sasanian province)|Pars]] and [[Khuzestan]] in Persia, in particular, to the new city of [[Veh-az-Amid Kavad]] (Arrajan).<ref>A. Shapur Shahbazi, Erich Kettenhofen, John R. Perry, \u201cDEPORTATIONS,\u201d ''[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Iranica]]'', VII/3, pp. 297-312, available online at http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/deportations (accessed on 30 December 2012).</ref>\n\n===Anastasius' campaign of 503 and Kavad I's counterattack===\n\nThe Byzantine emperor [[Anastasius I (emperor)|Anastasius I]] dispatched an army in May 503 against the Sasanians. The army was the largest Roman force in the East since [[Julian's Persian War|Julian's invasion of Persia]]. The force gathered at [[Edessa]] and [[Samosata]]. It operated in three divisions under ''[[magister militum per Orientem]]'' [[Areobindus Dagalaiphus Areobindus|Areobindus]], ''[[strategos]]'' [[Patricius (consul 500)|Patricius]], and [[Hypatius (consul 500)|Hypatius]]. Hypatius and Patricius attacked Amida, which was held by a 3,000-strong garrison under [[Glones]]. Areobindus, together with [[Romanus (dux)|Romanus]] and thee Arab ''[[phylarch]]'' Asouades (Aswad) (probably a [[Kindah]] leader) attacked [[Nisibis]], in which Kavadh I was residing.<ref name=\"Heather\">{{cite book |last1=Heather |first1=Peter J. |title=Rome Resurgent: War and Empire in the Age of Justinian |date=2018 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-936274-5 |page=77 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Shahid |first1=Irfan |title=Byzantium and the Arabs in the Sixth Century |date=1995 |publisher=Dumbarton Oaks |isbn=978-0-88402-214-5 |page=21 |language=en}}</ref> Procopius also mentions Patricias the Phrygian as a fourth commander.<ref name=\"Procopius62\" /> Notable officers associated with this force include ''\"[[hyparch]]\"'' [[Apion (family)|Apion I]] (the Egyptian),<ref>{{cite book |last1=Bury |first1=John Bagnell |title=History of the Later Roman Empire from the Death of Theodosius I. to the Death of Justinian |date=1958 |publisher=Courier Corporation |isbn=978-0-486-20398-0 |page=471 |language=en}}</ref> ''[[comes]]'' [[Justin I|Justin]] (the future emperor),<ref name=\"Dodgeon\" />  [[Patriciolus]] and his son [[Vitalian (general)|Vitalian]] (who later revolted against Anastasius), the Colchian [[Pharesmanes]], and the Goths Godidisklus and [[Bessas (general)|Bessas